Introduction to Naïve Bayes

The training session began with an introduction to Naïve Bayes, a probabilistic supervised Machine Learning algorithm used primarily for classification tasks. Learned that Naïve Bayes is based on Bayes' Theorem and assumes that all input features are independent of each other. Although this assumption is rarely true in real-world datasets, the algorithm performs remarkably well for many classification problems.

The trainer explained that Naïve Bayes is widely used because it is simple, computationally efficient, and capable of handling large datasets with high-dimensional features.

Discussed real-world applications such as email spam filtering, document classification, sentiment analysis, recommendation systems, and medical diagnosis.

Understanding Bayes' Theorem

Studied the mathematical foundation of the Naïve Bayes algorithm.

Learned the formula of Bayes' Theorem:

P(A|B) = (P(B|A) × P(A)) / P(B)

Where:

P(A|B) = Posterior Probability
P(B|A) = Likelihood
P(A) = Prior Probability
P(B) = Evidence

The trainer explained how Bayes' Theorem updates the probability of an event when new evidence becomes available.

