Independence Assumption

Learned the meaning of the Naïve Assumption, which states that all features are independent of one another.

Discussed why:

The assumption simplifies probability calculations.
The algorithm remains efficient even for large datasets.
Despite the assumption, Naïve Bayes often produces highly accurate results.

Compared independent and dependent features using practical examples.

Types of Naïve Bayes Algorithms

Studied different variants of the Naïve Bayes algorithm.

Gaussian Naïve Bayes
Used for continuous numerical data.
Assumes data follows a normal (Gaussian) distribution.

Applications:

Medical diagnosis
Student performance prediction
Multinomial Naïve Bayes
Used for discrete count data.
Commonly applied in text classification.

Applications:

Spam detection
News categorization
Document classification
Bernoulli Naïve Bayes
Used for binary features.
Works with data containing only 0 and 1 values.

Applications:

Email filtering
Binary text classification

Compared all three algorithms and discussed their suitable use cases.

